@{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

Do you have a program on your HD that needs as much memory as it can grab?
Does this mean you have to resort a tiny Startup-Sequence and/or rubbish
preferences, to save as much memory as possible upon booting? Well you need
do this no-longer.

StartE lets you have an extra 10 Startup-Sequences, that can be used to do
anything.  Take my 5 extra for example...

 @{fg shine}Huge Startup@{fg text}                - A nice huge memory hogging fancy one.
 @{fg shine}Tiny Startup@{fg text}                - A small Workbench that uses little RAM.
 @{fg shine}AWeb Startup@{fg text}                - Boots straight into AWeb browser.
 @{fg shine}The Settlers Startup@{fg text}        - Just runs The Settlers
 @{fg shine}Pinball Fantasies Startup@{fg text}   - Just runs Pinball Fantasies

These 5 startup sequences all work wonderfully, but having to rename them as
Startup-Sequence each time I wanted to use them, would become tedious.  This
is where StartE comes in.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "StartE/Usage"
@next "Author"
@prev "Introduction"
                             @{fg fill}StartE@{fg text} v1.1
                     © 1996 Brain Destruction S/W
                          Written By Burnsy

@{b}@{u}Usage@{ub}@{uu}

StartE is very simple to use.  The StartE program which should accompany
these docs does not have an icon, and should be copied to the C directory.
Then the following should be added to your Startup-Sequence...

@{fg shine} C:StartE
 If EXISTS RAM:Temp.BAT
    Execute RAM:Temp.BAT
 EndIf@{fg text}
 ...

This means, when you first boot, StartE will be run, it will check to see if
the right mouse button is held down, if so then the program will continue,
if not then it will quit back to your Startup-Sequence. Since @{fg highlight}RAM:Temp.BAT@{fg text}
will not exist, your startup will continue as normal. If however you hold
the right mouse button down during booting, then the program will attempt to
look for a file called @{fg highlight}S:StartupPrefs@{fg text}. If this is not found, StartE will
return an error.  @{fg highlight}S:StartupPrefs@{fg text} contains the information for your boot
menu. @{fg highlight}S:StartupPrefs@{fg text} can be created/edited using any ASCII text editor like
ED.  The first line of the file should be the menu title, with the remaining
lines made up as follows.

One line containingg the menu text for that option, then a line containing
the corresponding script file to use as the new Startup-Sequnce.

So my S:StartupPrefs is as follows

@{fg shine} Burnsy's Startup Enhancer
 Huge Startup
 S:Startups/Huge
 Tiny Startup
 S:Startups/Tiny
 AWeb Browser
 S:Startups/AWeb
 The Settlers
 S:Startups/Sett
 Pinball
 S:Startups/Pinball@{fg text}

StartE will then present you with the options, and wait for you to press the
corresponding number key, or the ESC key to abort.  If for example you
presses '2' to use the Tiny startup, then the file @{fg highlight}S:Startups/Tiny@{fg text} will be
copied to @{fg highlight}RAM:Temp.BAT@{fg text}, and so it would be executed.  So my startup would
consist of the contents of @{fg highlight}S:Startups/Tiny@{fg text} which is...

@{fg shine} LoadWB
 EndCLI@{fg text}

It's a good idea to end all your startups with EndCLI to prevent them from
returning to your original Startup-Sequence.

That's about it, if you have any problems @{"mail" link "Author" 0} me.
@endnode

